<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Strengths:</strong> Uptime is exceptional at 99.9997% despite being a massive fleet of 127 appliances. 715 non-disruptive upgrades have been completed successfully, showing an active operational cadence.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Concerns to address:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">All 126 of 127 appliances carry a <strong>"caution"</strong> support status — this is the primary flag requiring attention.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Contract hygiene</strong> is a real issue: 99 appliances have contracts expiring within the year, and several have already expired (as far back as late 2024). These need immediate renewal conversations.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Firmware fragmentation</strong>: 86 FlashArrays are on 6.5.9 while the latest is 6.10.4. The open Sev-4 master case for FA upgrades to 6.9.2 suggests this is already being tracked.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>5 open Sev-2 cases</strong> including controller interruption events and an RMA — these warrant close monitoring.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>gf2-purefb061-01</strong> FlashBlade has 3 open cases (upgrade, RMA, and blade replacement) — it's clearly a problem appliance.</li>
</ul></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
