ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great observation! The ESG charts actually do use Chart.js just like the others — so they do have hover tooltips on the bar and line charts. The parts that feel "non-interactive" are the <strong>impact equivalents section</strong> (trees, cars, racks, drives) and the <strong>illustrated elements</strong> (the forest SVG, the globe). Those are pure hand-coded SVG and HTML — static by design, since they're illustrations rather than data charts.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The reason I made that choice was purely aesthetic — illustrations don't have a natural "data point" to hover on, so adding tooltip behavior would feel forced. But the underlying Chart.js charts in that dashboard (energy comparison, reduction trend, utilization trend, capacity stack) all have full hover interactivity just like the other dashboards.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That said, the impact equivalent rows could absolutely be made interactive. A few directions we could go:</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
